caption: Incredibly friendly service to go along with delicious authentic Japanese cuisine

Hands down my favorite Japanese restaurant in Chicago. Very authentic. I especially love their takoyaki, hiyashi (cold ramen noodle, only served in summer), katsu don, rainbows & dragon rolls. The sweet plum wine is nice too!

Can't say enough lovely things about the food I got from Cocoro. The sushi was really fresh with beautiful flavors. Udon was also really delicious with high quality ingredients. Will definitely order and visit again soon. The lady who dropped off my food was very sweet as well - I think she must have been from the restaurant based on other reviews saying how kind she was. Thank you! Can't wait for our next order!!

This place is a hidden gem. It is the most authentic Japanese I've had outside of Japan. The women who run this place are very accommodating and have created a great atmosphere focused on brilliant food quality and superior service. There just aren't enough great things I can say about this place. I've taken at least 10 people here and now they all go there on they're own. It's that good! I'm telling you, go. I've had 80% of their menu and nothing has failed me yet.
Cozy atmosphere for a River North restaurant.  Not too loud, food is always good, lighting is comfortable.
Super fresh sushi!!
Cocoro is amazing! They have the freshest sushi in the city. Highly recommend.

The fish was fresh and the seaweed very crunchy. They served it one at a time as and when you finish a roll. The crab wasn't great though - a lot of mayo

The best sushi I have ever had. It is better and better every time I go. I wasn't a sushi lover but this place is absolutely amazing. It is owned and managed by a sweet Japanese woman.

OMG. One of the best authentic Japanese restaurants in town. It's not large but feels cozy. And the food is incredible. I go for the katsudon every time. It's simply amazing. I can't say enough about this place. Go, enjoy, and thank me later!
This place never disappoints. They have fresh dishes for reasonable rates, there is no waiting time even when the place is packed.

I didn't go there and give this review, but I went to a Japanese friend for three years, and sometimes it wasn't good either. And if you're not lucky, the waiting time is really long. Don't go. I visited a few weeks ago and I liked the decor. The one waitress has what is clearly either a wig on a perm but basically Shaka Khan hair and she is Asian. Now normally I don't mind but I was worried about the hair getting into things it was so big and clearly not natural. The hosts were nice but mostly overly friendly to the point that it seemed like an act and a little mocking. Many times I laughed at my waiter because I just couldn't take the exaggerated responses I got every time i asked for something. When he asked me if I had ever been there before I said no and he said "Welcome to Japanese food" like somehow me not eating there meant I had never had Japanese food before? It was an off experience to be sure. I ordered a bowl of shoyu ramen and it literally tasted like nothing. It was hot and the noodles were well cooked. The egg was not cooked correctly as it was hardboiled incorrectly (should be a little congealed in the center, not fully cooked) but literally the bowl tasted like nothing.NOTHING. (How do you do that?) I had to spice it to hell to give it a flavor. That is the first time I have ever had to do that to ramen and I have had bad ramen but there has always been a flavor.  The final straw for me and why I will not be back is the fact that in their over zealous need to make me *see* that the food is good or that they know what they are doing the owner came over and began to tell me the difference between the ramens after I had already finished and was looking to pay and trust me I didn't ask for the lesson. I will not be making the trip back soon.
Very nice: tasty food, wonderful service, good atmosphere. Three of us visited here recently it was perfect in every way.
Food is great, but the service is really really slow. Sometimes the waiter just totally forgot about you.

My favorite Japanese restaurant in Chicago! The food is great and the only authentic Japanese food I had tasted in Chicago. The service they provide is also awesome, everyone is kind and patient. Also it’s a good place for dining by yourself. Love cocoro~
I ordered the lunch sashimi-  it came with miso soup, pickled cabbage, tofu, sashimi and rice. The fish was fresh and the miso soup wasn't grainy like other places. The service was fast and pleasant.
This is by far the best sushi lunch that you can get in little Tokyo. The portion is pretty generous and the service is fast.

If you are looking for authentic Japanese food, look no further. This little restaurant has sukiyaki, shabu shabu, udon, curry, hot pots and soo much more. We had the shabu shabu and the pork curry, both were absolutely amazing. We had been looking for a good Japanese place after our recent trip to Japan, and this is so far, the best one we have found in the city. Will definitely be back soon.
Excellent spot to grab something when in a hurry. Their customer service is quick, prices are reasonable, awesome character. Would recommend to others
They are very friendly and the food was great

There were other places I visited, so I went for a walk, but if it was the destination from the beginning, a taxi would be good. I did not feel that it was a problem to walk in security. I am Japanese. This is the most authentic delicious Japanese restaurant in Chicago. I love it and my Japanese colleagues all love it.

CAUTION!! I don’t normally leave reviews, but this experience was particularly appalling so I have to say something.... they served me clearly bad fish, told me I was wrong, and then still expected me to pay for it even though it was unpalatable.  I went with some friends after work and I ordered a rainbow roll and some gyoza. As soon as the roll arrived, the whole table was filled with a foul “fish” smell, like a fish market. Anyone who knows fresh sushi knows this is a red flag.  I tried a piece anyway, and it left a foul fishy taste in my mouth. Others at the table tried a piece and agreed there was something wrong with the roll.  I very politely mentioned it to the waitress and she took the rest of the roll away... and returned with the owner who assured me the fish was fresh and tastes fine. I disagreed, stating I’ve had hundreds of rainbow rolls and this one was very clearly bad. The whole table reeked.  She then asked me which part of the roll was bad (seriously?) .... I said all of it. The two pieces I ate were not good. And she said specifically which part, so I said I tried the salmon and tuna. And she returned with the sushi chef and a plate with a salmon fillet on it... she then points at the chef and told me “he would know if the fish is fresh, he knows the taste”. And refused to acknowledge that they served me a bad roll.  They literally served me bad fish, told me I was wrong, and then made me pay for it.  I will never eat at this restaurant again, and neither will any of my friends who were there to witness me being flat-out robbed by this place.  I highly suggest you find a different restaurant for sushi. Seriously.

Food looked good but a couple of the rolls were loosely rolled and fell apart easily. One roll had very mushy asparagus. Restaurant had just opened for lunch so maybe was just an off day. Restaurant was clean and good environment.

Worst restaurant experience I can remember.  1 hour after ordering still no food. Finally said something to one of the waiters who proceeded to act like he hadn't noticed us, then said he was going to go check and then proceeded to never return.  At 845 we walked out, said goodbye to 2 of the 4 staff who seemed happy to not have to let us know they never put the food in. We never received an update, , an apology for being late, and most importantly no food 1 hour and 15 mins after being seated.  True zero star experience.

I am not a Japanese food expert by any means, but this restaurant has only limited options compared to everywhere else I have been to. I do not eat sea food, and this restaurant is not a suitable location for someone like me. I can't judge the seafood, but from the way my colleagues were eating their food I suspect it was delicious. Service was amazing and very nice. I just wished they had a few more non seafood options and more ways of cooking. They had more pork options as well, but I don't eat pork.
Delicious food, loved everything we ordered. Recommend the beef asparagus, shrimp dumplings and crispy tuna roll. We’ll be back!

they have really nice taste
Excellent sushi and Katsu curry, decent liqour prices, and great service.
Authentic Japanese food, just like in Tokyo.
Delicious food and kind, quick service. Thank you!

Fresh sushi. Delicious and reasonable price. Good service.

The establishment and service seems homemade but charming, in an anti-corporate sort of way. In a great location in River North, I would highly suggest to them an investment in a professional branding/marketing designer, because I had not heard of it, and the only reason I found it was because I really wanted Udon. Their beef Udon soup was the epitome of savory, umami goodness. Somehow it heated up even better in the microwave the next day. I ordered mine extra spicy and they gave me cayenne and chili oil on the side. Delicious! If you’re not a fan of mushrooms, I would ask for them taken out; if you are a fan of a variety of Japanese mushrooms, you’re in luck! Fried chicken appetizer was d e l i c i o u s, crispy and savory dark meat in a unique breading, I REALLY wish it came with sweet & sour sauce. Gyozas were delicate and also savory. Did not care for the tough texture of the octopus balls. Service was okay, it was hard to get their attention when we wanted to leave. Bathroom was unfortunate :(
Food was yummy but not spectacular, and we waited over an hour before getting it, and it wasn't very busy!
One of the top sushi places in River North.
Authentic and pleasant.

Friendly service. The pickles are amazing! I was sad they didn't include mine in my left overs though. The miso soup was standard, but better than average tofu in it was a happy surprise. My katsu curry was decent, not the best I have had, but very fair portion size! Overall I certainly will go try other items here based on the things my neighboring takes were saying about the teriaki, and sushi!

Cute small places, way overrated!  The food was below expectation! The 10 piece cocoro roll was just ok but the eel with rice was  a bit better. Don’t recommend either one anyway! The service was poor. Had to wait a lot to receive attention - they do seem understaffed! Once the place got busy the quality of service decreased dramatically.
The food is delicious!

We went to Takoba for a work lunch as it's around the corner from our office, but it's definitely more than a quick grab and go. Their sushi is super tasty and everyone enjoyed it. I had the miso soup and John Collins and it was so so good. Would recommend!
I like this place. Food is so good.
Authentic Japanese cusine. Sashimi was fresh and delicious. Portions were a little small but quality was good regardless.
Great lunch specials! Super chill and reasonably priced for downtown.
Great katsu curry pork the best I've tasted outside of Tokyo.

If your looking for unpretentious authentic Japanese food, Cocoro is the only spot you need to know about. It's small, and unassuming, but the fact that its always packed with Japanese and Asian customers just goes to show its the real deal.
Traditional Japanese, and more.  Cocoro offers a wide range of dishes --. Hot & cold, cooked & raw.
Amazing

Authentic Japanese. Make a rez. Been going there for 20 years.

The place looks nice. But they are making food too long. We with my colleague were there after 1 PM and there were 4 people sitting there. We were waiting for food, rolls and noodle soup, about 30 minutes. Rolls were tasty, but soup is not too much... maybe it's just my bad experience...
One of very few authentic Japanese food spots in Chicago that doesn't cost an arm and leg. Japanese owners have been around 20+ years.

Never disappointed at this place. This is like my spot to go at least one time in summer for that COLD RAMEN and Takoyaki. I wait for summer to come just for this. Other than these two items on the menu try out any dish , it will be fresh and good. I recommend the sushi and sashimi as it’s really fresh ingredients
Nice little restaurant. Takoyaki was good. Eel serie was also good and with a reasonable size. There was just one chef there so we waited a really long time. But the food was nice.

The venue is nice, I went around lunch so it was packed. I ordered veggie Udon, I wanted veggie ramen but they didn't have a veggie ramen broth but the Udon broth was completely veggie. I guess you can't switch broths. The Udon dish was okay, I had to add quite a bit of flavor to make ot more flavorful. My niece ordered the beef curry it was really good, the flavors blended well. The curry was a nice dark color.  The waitress was really good, especially considering the fact she was the only waitress in the entire restuarant. We went around lunch time, so if you have time and don't mind the wait it's a good place to eat. If you need something a little quicker I would suggest going somewhere else, you definitely wouldn't have enough time.

Amazing atmosphere, people, and food. The people who work there are Japanese, and the sushi chef seems to be very authentic and has been making sushi for a very long time. A very relaxed atmosphere the lights a dim (to a nice point), and the music is some nice chill jazz. I ordered the Cocoro Combo number 1, which comes with an assortment of raw fish and a California roll. The raw fish did not have a fishy taste, and it was delicious and well worth the money. Highly recommend.
Traditional Japanese, I had one of the best Katsu chicken outside Japan!
Some of the best sashimi in town. Well worth the wait.
Best Japanese food in the neighborhood.  Traditional and authentic dishes without the pretentiousness of some of the flashier Japanese restaurants in River North

Hidden gem in River North... I’ve walked by Cocoro many times and never even noticed it was here. Finally s friend suggested it and we checked it out, and I was pleasantly surprised by the offerings and atmosphere.  We had the egg custard, katsu dinner plate, and spicy katsu ramen. All were really good! I’ll definitely be back again in the future.

Great lunch spot. Glad it did not get taken down for the new building next store. The staff is extremely friendly. Very authentic place, but they don't make you feel bad for being inexperienced in Asian food. Wide variety of choices and prices are reasonable.
Expensive but worth it. The only place you can find the legit(....ish) sushi, which is with seasoned rice in downtown Chicago.
Best authentic japanese food on this side of the Mississippi! Hands down my favorite meal in chicago. If you dont know what to order just ask and youll always be satisfied!

I've been coming since college... It's been 8 years and it's still awesome food. If you want Japanese food, made by Japanese people, this is the place for you. Authentic. Japanese. Food.

I was craving sushi and stumbled across this place. Not the best sushi experience but the tempura udon was filling. Although the udon does not taste homemade the broth tasted very authentic and flavourful.
The food, for its price is on point I'll give you that. Quick tip for pick orders, call ahead before going there. Takes a couple mins! Cool place to go to for a date!

Excellent little spot. Good selection of real Japanese small plates, and tempura. The sushi is top notch. Large slabs of fish over the small pieces of rice with the perfect amount of wasabi in between. The Chu-toro would melt in your mouth seconds after touching it, releasing an intense flavor. The hamachi was fresh. Good sake selection  We saw tables nearby having Shabu shabu which looked great, and will definitely try it sometime in the near future.

If you want Japanese food other than ramen in downtown area, this is probably the best option. You might feel the service is mediocre unless you speak fluent Japanese language, but the food is authentic and some famous Japanese athletes also visit this place before their matches.
(Translated by Google) I liked the place and the very delicious food but they take a long time to attend  (Original) Me gustó el lugar y la comida muy rica pero tardan mucho para atender
Absolutely love it , shabu-shabu my favorite.

Consistently the best sushi and Japanese food in general downtown (perhaps the entire city). Go with the sashimi chef selection if you're feeling like sushi. In terms of other items, their curry, tonkotsu and various small plates have always hit the spot, but honestly everything I've ordered here has been good. No frills interior and relaxed service, but who cares? I'm here for the food anyway! :)
Very authentic! Great ramen 👌🏻
Like eating in Japan.

They do serve sushi but this place, to me, is best for home cooked Japanese food. Their nabanyaki udon is delicious. Sake selection is pretty decent. Considering the Sumi up the street closed, a good alternative for traditional Japanese.

This is as close as you're going to get to authentic Japanese comfort food. Really chill atmosphere great staff and consistency when it comes to flavours. Watch out for the weekday dinner hours the Japanese business men fill the place up 😂😂😂 great experience every time. The shabushabu is a little small though.

I came here for a quick lunch and as I do at any Japanese restaurant, I ordered ramen. I got the shio ramen from there which came with an half an egg and a slice of pork belly. The food came out timely and the staff was friendly the whole time. The ramen though was very subpar. The noodles themselves looked and tasted like something you'd grab out of a bag of Maruchan. The broth wasn't very flavorful either. The egg was hardboiled and cold in the center as opposed to soft boiled and having that molten yolk I crave when grabbing ramen. The pork too was not flavorful at all and tasted as if it had no seasoning. Overall this ramen was just very meh. Considering all the other amazing ramen spots in the city, this isn't somewhere I will be coming again. Not for ramen at least.
Fairly slow service but the food is superior. Not your regular chain Japanese restaurant. The food is traditional and authentic,  tastes like from a family kitchen.

a little pricey but the sushi is very good.

Cocoro is one of the best Japanese restaurants in Chicago with some of the tastiest dishes you'll find that represent fairly traditional Japanese dishes. Some of my go tos include the tonkatsu, sushi, grilled mackerel, and chicken karaage. Cocoro is an absolute gem in Chicago, and easily accessible as well. If you're a fan of Japanese cuisine, absolutely add this one to your list, and I'm confident that it'll make it into your regular rotation.
Great sushi for sushi lovers. Lots of Japanese goodies.
Loved the ambiance and the staff was super energetic. I ordered the miso ramen and it was very flavorful. Overally a great ramen place to check out!
Ate here a couple of years ago.. Went again and it was packed... Was looking to have shabu shabu which was a great experience then.

This is in my top 5 and this is my 10 year old daughter and wife's favorite restaurant. We've been coming her for over 5 years and have never had a bad experience. The owner is such a sweetheart and my daughter has some hello kitty souvenirs from her. We love the ramen and the Shubu Shubu for two. Red bean ice cream is so unique. Please stop in and allow Yoko to blow you away.
One of my favorite places. Low key restaurant with traditional Japanese food. Always very fresh and interesting recipes. The staff is very friendly.

Food was served quickly once they took our orders and the Tonkotsu Ramen was really good. It doesn't come with an egg, I believe you need to order on the side. The broth was delicious although I was not a fan of the ginger bits in the soup. The sesame was a nice touch. The Pork was falling apart-- so delicious! The noodle was firm and good for Ramen standards. I think their portion is bigger (at least noodle and broth) than other ramen places in town in my opinion. The service was friendly and attentive.

I have been coming here for more than 3yrs now. Never ever disappointed my appetite once. Their quality is one of the top authentic Japanese restaurant in Chicago but you will like their affordable price for sure. I bring everyone of my good friends, girlfriend, parents etc to this place to share my awesome experience with them.
This restaurant has a great menu,  nice starters and have drink specials.

As a person who's being too almost all the Ramen shops in Chicago, Cocoro has lower than average quality Ramen. Broth is really runny, no consistency; too much scallion, no flavor whatsoever. Anyway if you're looking for good Ramen, do not come to this place.

Super friendly service.  Fast preparation and cozy quarter.  Next time we will wait to put our main dish in a little after app comes out so we have a breather. Stuck with the sushi and was delicious!  Look forward to exploring their menu
Top notch sushi, ramen, and other items.  Very friendly and courteous.  Not stuffy or pretentious.  Excellent all around!!

The most authentic Japanese restaurant I have found in the area.  You will see a lot of Japanese people eating here and enjoying the selections.  Large menu you with multiple ramen dishes and fantastic appetizers.  Haven't tried the sushi yet but there is a sushi bar inside.
This was one of the only place that doesn't just flavour food with salt. Thoroughly enjoyed eating. Staff was friendly and food was served quickly.

Really good ramen.  All 4 basic types, with a spicy option for miso.  Reminds me of what I had in Japan.

I lived in Japan 5 years. Love fusion too but this real Japanese food. Kitchen food. The Sushi they just do. And their fish is so fresh. Not like some other ethnic Sushi places. Its the specials here that rule. Real Japanese home and restaurant food.
Came in for some sushi. Had their super spicy tuna and dragon roll. Both were excellent! I'd come back

my favorite Japanese restaurant in Chicago. Their shabu shabu and udon are the best!! Sushi was not as nice as other made dishes...but I went back to this place more than 5 times for last 3 month. that's how much i like this place. They do also delivery. but close on Sundays.
